# Ephemeral / machine-local — these are generated artifacts.
#
# Why ignore the whole data/ JSON surface (vs. checking it in):
#   - optimized_prompt.json embeds whole SKILL.md snapshots that drift from
#     the live skill within a few iterations; a stale checked-in copy
#     teaches the optimizer to reproduce yesterday's mistakes (and worse,
#     the schema has expanded over time, so old copies are silently
#     incompatible with the current loader).
#   - tuned_thresholds.json is an Optuna fit on whatever eval history this
#     machine happens to have. With < ~5 skill sequences it is effectively
#     a noise sample; checking it in implies "global default" when it is
#     not.
#   - trigger_eval_set.json is regenerated cheaply on demand; the
#     committed copy goes stale the moment the description changes.
#
# Producers regenerate these on demand:
#   python scripts/collect_evals.py
#   python scripts/optimize.py
#   python scripts/optimize_description.py
#   uv run scripts/tune_thresholds.py
data/*.jsonl
data/*.json

review/

# projects/<name>/v<N>/ — versioned eval metadata.
#
# We INTENTIONALLY commit eval.json / input.md / changes.md / skill.md so:
#   - data/evals.jsonl is genuinely regenerable from `collect_evals.py`
#     across machines and CI (the docs in references/evals/index.md and
#     scaffold/atoms/versioned-projects.md both depend on this);
#   - `collect_evals.py`'s git-history fallback for the SKILL.md snapshot
#     can actually find the eval.json commit;
#   - rollbacks and version-to-version comparisons reviewers do in PRs
#     work without out-of-band sharing.
#
# We ignore everything else under projects/ — generated outputs, sandbox
# runs, scratch dirs — because those are heavy and per-machine.
projects/*/v*/output/
projects/*/v*/sandbox/
projects/*/runs/
projects/*/sandbox/

__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
